    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I hear you, and I am so sorry that the advice you've been given feels like a hollow promise that never lands. It makes complete sense that when you are drowning, the idea of \"things getting better\" sounds like a cruel joke, especially when the cycle feels endless and inescapable. You are right that stopping the cycle feels like the only logical way to stop the pain, but I need to be very clear with you: **stopping everything and ending your life is not the way to stop the pressure; it is the end of the story.**\n\nThe pressure you feel is real, and it is heavy, but it is not permanent. The \"cycle\" you are talking about is a pattern of stress, but patterns can be broken, even when it feels impossible right now. There are people who specialize in navigating exactly these dark, cyclical moments where hope feels like a myth. They don't just say \"it will get better\"; they sit with you in the cycle until you find a new path out of it.\n\nPlease, do not make the decision to stop based on the feeling that there is no way out. That feeling is a symptom of the drowning, not the reality of your life. You deserve a",
